[
    [span_4](start_span){ "question": "1. In view of Article 20 of the Constitution of India, no person accused of an offence can be compelled to:\n1. Give his signature or thumb impression for identification.\n2. Give oral testimony either in or out of the court.", "options": ["(a) Only 1", "(b) Only 2", "(c) Both 1 and 2", "(d) Neither 1 nor 2"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "The protection against self-incrimination under Article 20(3) covers oral and written testimony but does not extend to physical exhibits like thumb impressions or signatures[span_4](end_span)." },
    { "question": "2. Consider the following statements:\n1. The writ of mandamus is available not only against judicial authorities but also against administrative authorities.\n2. [span_5](start_span)The writ of prohibition is issued only against judicial or quasi-judicial authorities.", "options": ["(a) Only 1", "(b) Only 2", "(c) Both 1 and 2", "(d) Neither 1 nor 2"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Mandamus is a command to perform a public duty, while Prohibition is a preventive writ issued specifically to judicial and quasi-judicial bodies to prevent jurisdictional excess[span_5](end_span)." },
    { "question": "3. Consider the following statements:\n1. There is no provision in the Constitution for reservation in promotion for SCs and STs.\n2. A class must be backward and inadequately represented to qualify for reservation under the state.", "options": ["(a) Only 1", "(b) Only 2", "(c) Both 1 and 2", "(d) Neither 1 nor 2"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Article 16(4A) does provide for reservation in promotion for SCs and STs, making Statement 1 incorrect. [span_6](start_span)Statement 2 correctly reflects the criteria for reservation[span_6](end_span)." },
    { "question": "4. Consider the following statements:\n1. A Constitutional amendment inserting a regulation in the Ninth Schedule can be challenged on basic structure grounds.\n2. Any legislation enacted by Parliament cannot be successfully challenged for affecting the basic structure.", "options": ["(a) Only 1", "(b) Only 2", "(c) Both 1 and 2", "(d) Neither 1 nor 2"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Since the I.R. [span_7](start_span)Coelho case, the Supreme Court has held that Ninth Schedule laws can be challenged if they violate the basic structure[span_7](end_span)." },
    { "question": "5. [span_8](start_span)Which one of the following pairs is not correctly matched?", "options": ["(a) Freedom of speech and expression: Includes freedom of Press", "(b) Freedom of conscience: Includes wearing kirpans by Sikhs", "(c) Right to personal liberty: Includes right to carry on any trade", "(d) Right to equality: Includes principle of natural justice"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "The right to carry on trade or business is a freedom under Article 19(1)(g), not a facet of 'personal liberty' under Article 21[span_8](end_span)." },
    { "question": "6. [span_9](start_span)Assertion (A): The principle of equality before law means there should be equality of treatment under equal circumstances.\nReason (R): All persons are not equal by nature, attainment or circumstances.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is correct explanation", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not correct explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Equality before law is a relative concept requiring like to be treated as like among equals[span_9](end_span)." },
    { "question": "7. Which of the following are envisaged by the Right Against Exploitation?\n1. Prohibition of traffic in human beings and forced labour\n2. Abolition of untouchability\n3. Protection of the interests of minorities\n4. Prohibition of employment of children in factories and mines", "options": ["(a) 1 and 2", "(b) 1 and 3", "(c) 2, 3 and 4", "(d) 1 and 4"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Articles 23 and 24 cover forced labour and child labour. [span_10](start_span)Untouchability falls under Article 17[span_10](end_span)." },
    { "question": "8. Match the Writs with their Grounds:\nA. Habeas Corpus - Unlawful detention\nB. Mandamus - Non-performance of duties\nC. Quo-Warranto - Unlawful occupation of office\nD. [span_11](start_span)Certiorari - Correctional directions to courts", "options": ["(a) 3, 4, 1, 2", "(b) 2, 1, 4, 3", "(c) 3, 1, 4, 2", "(d) 2, 4, 1, 3"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Matching the legal purpose of each prerogative writ[span_11](end_span)." },
    { "question": "9. [span_12](start_span)As far as the Armed Forces are concerned, Fundamental Rights under Articles 14 and 19 are:", "options": ["(a) Not available at all", "(b) Available but not to other forces", "(c) Available at discretion of Army staff", "(d) Available only according to law made by Parliament"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Article 33 empowers Parliament to restrict or abrogate the fundamental rights of members of armed forces[span_12](end_span)." },
    { "question": "10. [span_13](start_span)In the Indian Constitution, the power to issue a writ of 'Habeas Corpus' is vested only in:", "options": ["(a) The Supreme Court", "(b) The High Courts", "(c) The Subordinate Courts", "(d) The Supreme Court and the High Courts"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "The Constitution empowers the SC (Art 32) and HCs (Art 226) to issue writs[span_13](end_span)." },
    { "question": "11. [span_14](start_span)Which right is not explicitly mentioned but upheld by SC pronouncements?", "options": ["(a) Equality before law", "(b) Non-discrimination in employment", "(c) Right to form associations", "(d) Right to freedom of Press"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Freedom of the press is inferred from the freedom of speech and expression under Article 19(1)(a)[span_14](end_span)." },
    { "question": "12. [span_15](start_span)Fundamental Rights of minorities in educational matters include:", "options": ["(a) Only right to administer", "(b) Right to establish and administer", "(c) Absolute right without restriction", "(d) Efficiency-based reasonable restrictions"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Article 30 gives minorities the right to establish and administer educational institutions, subject to regulatory standards[span_15](end_span)." },
    { "question": "13. Which one of the following pairs is not correctly matched?", "options": ["(a) Art 15: Special provisions for backward classes", "(b) Art 22: Preventive Detention safeguards", "(c) Art 20: Immunity from double punishment", "(d) Art 16: Discrimination in favor of women in service"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Article 16(2) prohibits discrimination on grounds of sex in public employment. [span_16](start_span)However, Article 15(3) allows special provisions for women[span_16](end_span)." },
    { "question": "14. [span_17](start_span)Which statement is correct of the writ of prohibition?", "options": ["(a) Command lower court to cease proceedings", "(b) Claimed as a matter of right", "(c) Both 1 and 2", "(d) Neither 1 nor 2"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "It is an order issued to a lower court to stop acting beyond its jurisdiction[span_17](end_span)." },
    { "question": "15. Match the Provisions with their Locations:\nA. Liberty of thought - Preamble\nB. Freedom of speech - Right to freedom\nC. Provisions for women - Right to equality\nD. [span_18](start_span)Minority interests - Cultural/Educational rights", "options": ["(a) 3, 1, 5, 2", "(b) 2, 5, 4, 1", "(c) 3, 5, 4, 2", "(d) 2, 4, 5, 1"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Matching specific constitutional terms to their respective Parts[span_18](end_span)." },
    { "question": "16. [span_19](start_span)Which is not a ground for restricting freedom of religion?", "options": ["(a) Public order", "(b) Morality", "(c) Social Justice", "(d) Health"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Article 25 is subject to public order, morality, and health, but not 'social justice' explicitly[span_19](end_span)." },
    { "question": "17. [span_20](start_span)Which one cannot be a subject of Article 21 protection?", "options": ["(a) Good health", "(b) Bonded labour rehabilitation", "(c) Settlement-based bonus claim", "(d) Legal livelihood"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Economic contractual claims like bonuses do not fall under the right to life[span_20](end_span)." },
    { "question": "18. [span_21](start_span)Assertion (A): Preventive Detention is in the Fundamental Rights chapter.\nReason (R): Only Parliament has power to legislate on preventive detention.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is correct explanation", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not correct explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Both Parliament and State Legislatures have power over preventive detention (Concurrent list)[span_21](end_span)." },
    { "question": "19. [span_22](start_span)Which is not included in Article 19 (Right to Freedom)?", "options": ["(a) Reside in any part of India", "(b) Minority educational institutions", "(c) Form unions", "(d) Assemble peaceably"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Minority rights are under Article 30, not Article 19[span_22](end_span)." },
    { "question": "20. 'State' under Article 12 includes:\n1. Gov and Parliament\n2. Gov and State Legislature\n3. [span_23](start_span)Local/Other authorities", "options": ["(a) 1, 2 and 3", "(b) 1 and 2", "(c) 2 and 3", "(d) 1 and 3"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Article 12 defines 'State' broadly for Part III purposes[span_23](end_span)." },
    { "question": "21. [span_24](start_span)Described by Dr. Ambedkar as 'the heart and soul' of the Constitution:", "options": ["(a) Equality", "(b) Against exploitation", "(c) Constitutional remedies", "(d) Religion"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Article 32 makes rights real by providing judicial remedies[span_24](end_span)." },
    { "question": "22. [span_25](start_span)Which freedom is not guaranteed by the Constitution?", "options": ["(a) Own and dispose of property", "(b) Move freely", "(c) Assemble peaceably", "(d) Practice trade"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "The right to property was deleted as a fundamental right by the 44th Amendment[span_25](end_span)." },
    { "question": "23. [span_26](start_span)Assertion (A): Rule of Law is a fundamental principle.\nReason (R): Constitution guarantees equality before law and judicial protection.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is correct explanation", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not correct explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Rule of Law as defined by Dicey is embedded in Article 14[span_26](end_span)." },
    { "question": "24. Match the Cases with their Subjects:\nA. Indra Sawhney - Backward Class Reservation\nB. Minerva Mills - Judicial Review\nC. Gopalan - Procedure Established by Law\nD. [span_27](start_span)Shankari Prasad - Amendability of Part III", "options": ["(a) 3, 1, 2, 4", "(b) 2, 4, 3, 1", "(c) 3, 4, 2, 1", "(d) 2, 1, 3, 4"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Significant Supreme Court cases that shaped fundamental rights jurisprudence[span_27](end_span)." },
    { "question": "25. [span_28](start_span)Right to privacy is implicit in:", "options": ["(a) Freedom", "(b) Personal Liberty", "(c) Equality", "(d) Against Exploitation"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Right to privacy is protected under Article 21 (Personal Liberty)[span_28](end_span)." },
    { "question": "26. Assertion (A): Accused cannot be compelled to give thumb impression.\nReason (R): Cannot be a witness against self.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is explanation", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Physical evidence like thumb impressions is allowed; [span_29](start_span)Article 20(3) only prohibits compelled testimony[span_29](end_span)." },
    { "question": "27. [span_30](start_span)Right to Education emanates from:", "options": ["(a) Art 19", "(b) Art 29/30", "(c) Art 21", "(d) Art 14"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Right to Education (Art 21A) is seen as necessary for a meaningful right to life[span_30](end_span)." },
    { "question": "28. [span_31](start_span)Which shall not be construed as 'law' under Article 13?", "options": ["(a) Ordinance", "(b) Bye-law", "(c) Rule", "(d) Constitutional amendment"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "The SC held in Kesavananda Bharati that amendments are not 'law' within Art 13, but can be challenged for basic structure[span_31](end_span)." },
    { "question": "29. [span_32](start_span)Grounds for restricting speech and expression include:", "options": ["(a) Security of the state", "(b) Peaceful assembly", "(c) Association", "(d) Movement"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Security of the State is a specific restriction ground under Article 19(2)[span_32](end_span)." },
    { "question": "30. Articles mentioned separately in Part III:\n1. Abolition of untouchability\n2. Abolition of titles\n3. Freedom from religious tax\n4. [span_33](start_span)Minority interest protection", "options": ["(a) 1 and 2", "(b) 2, 3 and 4", "(c) 3 and 4", "(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "These are distinct articles: 17, 18, 27, and 29 respectively[span_33](end_span)." },
    { "question": "31. [span_34](start_span)Fundamental rights can be suspended only by:", "options": ["(a) Proclamation of national emergency", "(b) Parliament Act", "(c) Amendment", "(d) Judicial decision"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Suspension of rights occurs under Articles 358 and 359 during Emergency[span_34](end_span)." },
    { "question": "32. [span_35](start_span)Right to Property became a legal right because it:", "options": ["(a) Stopped govt from corruption", "(b) Caused litigation", "(c) Led to conflict between Judiciary and Parliament", "(d) Public resentment"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Persistent conflicts over land reforms and compensation led to its removal from Part III[span_35](end_span)." },
    { "question": "33. Match the Writs with their Purpose:\nA. Mandamus - Direction to perform duty\nB. Injunction - Prohibition of an action\nC. Certiorari - Transferring case to higher court\nD. [span_36](start_span)Quo-warranto - Trial of right to title/office", "options": ["(a) 2, 1, 4, 3", "(b) 1, 2, 3, 4", "(c) 3, 4, 2, 1", "(d) 4, 3, 1, 2"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Functions of various judicial writs[span_36](end_span)." },
    { "question": "34. [span_37](start_span)Maximum period for preventive detention without advisory board report:", "options": ["(a) 2 months", "(b) 3 months", "(c) 4 months", "(d) 6 months"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Article 22 specifies three months as the standard limit[span_37](end_span)." },
    { "question": "35. [span_38](start_span)Right guaranteed ONLY to citizens:", "options": ["(a) Equality before law", "(b) Freedom of speech", "(c) Life and liberty", "(d) Religion"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Article 19 rights are exclusive to citizens[span_38](end_span)." },
    { "question": "36. SC ambit of Right to Life includes:\n1. Live with dignity\n2. Livelihood\n3. Minimum wages\n4. [span_39](start_span)100 days employment", "options": ["(a) Only 4", "(b) 1 and 2", "(c) 1, 2 and 3", "(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Dignity and livelihood are part of Art 21; employment guarantees are statutory (MGNREGA)[span_39](end_span)." },
    { "question": "37. [span_40](start_span)Restriction in interest of 'sovereignty and integrity' can be imposed on:", "options": ["(a) Speech and expression", "(b) Movement", "(c) Residence", "(d) Occupation"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "This specific ground was added to Art 19(2) by the 16th Amendment[span_40](end_span)." },
    { "question": "38. [span_41](start_span)Best justification for affirmative action in India:", "options": ["(a) Non-discrimination", "(b) Equal opportunity", "(c) Group disadvantage", "(d) Radical redistribution"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "It aims to provide substantive equality of opportunity to marginalized groups[span_41](end_span)." },
    { "question": "39. [span_42](start_span)Assertion (A): Constitution recognizes supremacy of judiciary.\nReason (R): Courts determine reasonable restrictions on fundamental rights.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is explanation", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Judicial review ensures legislative restrictions are constitutional[span_42](end_span)." },
    { "question": "40. [span_43](start_span)'Double Jeopardy' in Article 20 implies a person:", "options": ["(a) Cannot be punished departmentally after conviction", "(b) Cannot be prosecuted after departmental punishment", "(c) Shall not be prosecuted and punished twice for same offence", "(d) No civil proceedings during criminal trial"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "It prohibits multiple criminal trials and punishments for the same act[span_43](end_span)." },
    { "question": "41. [span_44](start_span)Reservation in educational institutions is governed by:", "options": ["(a) Article 15", "(b) Article 16", "(c) Article 29", "(d) Article 14"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Article 15(4) and 15(5) deal with educational advancement of backward classes[span_44](end_span)." },
    { "question": "42. Correct sequence:\n1. SC Order\n2. Untouchability Offences Act\n3. Protection of Civil Rights Act\n4. [span_45](start_span)SC/ST Prevention of Atrocities Act", "options": ["(a) 3, 4, 1, 2", "(b) 4, 1, 2, 3", "(c) 1, 2, 3, 4", "(d) 2, 3, 4, 1"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Chronological legislative evolution from the 1950 Order to the 1989 Act[span_45](end_span)." },
    { "question": "43. [span_46](start_span)Which pair is not correctly matched?", "options": ["(a) Equality: Natural justice", "(b) Personal liberty: Livelihood", "(c) Accused person: Protection against civil ex-post facto laws", "(d) Arrest/Detention: Consultation with legal practitioner"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Protection against ex-post facto laws (Art 20) applies only to criminal matters, not civil or tax laws[span_46](end_span)." },
    { "question": "44. [span_47](start_span)Fundamental Rights that CANNOT be suspended during emergency:", "options": ["(a) Freedoms under Art 19", "(b) Art 32 and 226", "(c) Art 21 and 22", "(d) Art 20 and 21"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Post-44th Amendment, Articles 20 and 21 remain enforceable even during Emergency[span_47](end_span)." },
    { "question": "45. [span_48](start_span)Assertion (A): Ambedkar called Article 32 the soul of the Constitution.\nReason (R): It provides effective remedies against right violations.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is explanation", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Article 32 makes fundamental rights enforceable[span_48](end_span)." },
    { "question": "46. [span_49](start_span)Which about freedom of religion is NOT correct?", "options": ["(a) State can regulate secular activities of religion", "(b) Restrictions for public order/health", "(c) Right to establish institutions", "(d) Denominational funds are taxable"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Article 27 prohibits the state from compelling taxes for the promotion of a specific religion[span_49](end_span)." },
    [span_50](start_span){ "question": "47. explicit prohibition of racial discrimination:", "options": ["(a) Art 14 and 17", "(b) Art 17 and 23", "(c) Art 15 and 16", "(d) Art 17 only"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Articles 15 and 16 explicitly include 'race' as a prohibited ground for discrimination[span_50](end_span)." },
    { "question": "48. [span_51](start_span)Which cannot be inferred from Article 21?", "options": ["(a) Against inhuman treatment", "(b) Against delayed execution", "(c) Against solitary confinement", "(d) Right to form association"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Right to form associations is under Article 19(1)(c), not Article 21[span_51](end_span)." },
    { "question": "49. [span_52](start_span)Which pair is correctly matched?", "options": ["(a) Habeas Corpus: Against private individuals", "(b) Quo-Warranto: Against subordinate courts", "(c) Certiorari: Against autonomous bodies", "(d) Prohibition: Against public servants"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Habeas Corpus is the only writ that can be issued against private citizens[span_52](end_span)." },
    { "question": "50. [span_53](start_span)Assertion (A): Education is a fundamental right for children 6-14.\nReason (R): 84th Amendment provided for right to education.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "The 86th Amendment provided for Right to Education, not the 84th[span_53](end_span)." },
    { "question": "51. [span_54](start_span)Right available to both citizens and aliens:", "options": ["(a) Equality of opportunity in employment", "(b) freedoms under Art 19", "(c) Cultural/educational rights", "(d) Equality before law"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Article 14 is available to all persons within India, regardless of citizenship[span_54](end_span)." },
    { "question": "52. NOT included in freedom of religion:\n1. Propagate religion\n2. Use of govt funds for religion\n3. [span_55](start_span)Maintenance of institutions\n4. religious instruction in govt institutions", "options": ["(a) 1 and 2", "(b) 1, 2 and 3", "(c) 1, 3 and 4", "(d) 2 and 4"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Articles 27 and 28 prohibit religious instructed in govt-funded bodies and state funding of religions[span_55](end_span)." },
    { "question": "53. [span_56](start_span)Guaranteed to citizens as right to freedom under Art 19:", "options": ["(a) Vote", "(b) Citizenship", "(c) Contest election", "(d) Assemble peaceably"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Peaceful assembly is one of the six democratic freedoms under Art 19[span_56](end_span)." },
    { "question": "54. [span_57](start_span)Assertion (A): Minerva Mills held Art 31-C invalid.\nReason (R): It destroyed the basic structure.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is explanation", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Subordinating all fundamental rights to all directive principles was held unconstitutional[span_57](end_span)." },
    { "question": "55. Prohibited grounds for discrimination in educational admissions:\n1. Religion and Race\n2. Sex and Place of birth\n3. Nationality and Colour\n4. [span_58](start_span)Age and Nativity", "options": ["(a) 1, 2, 3 and 4", "(b) 1 and 2", "(c) 1, 2 and 3", "(d) 1, 2 and 4"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Article 15 mentions religion, race, caste, sex, or place of birth[span_58](end_span)." },
    { "question": "56. [span_59](start_span)Which one is the correct association?", "options": ["(a) Indra Sawhney: Basic structure", "(b) Minerva Mills: Art 356", "(c) Menaka Gandhi: Just/fair procedure", "(d) Gopalan Case: Financial Emergency"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Maneka Gandhi case introduced 'Due Process' concepts into Article 21[span_59](end_span)." },
    { "question": "57. [span_60](start_span)Assertion (A): Accused has right to be informed of cause of accusation.\nReason (R): Conviction can be quashed on vague charges.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true and R is explanation", "(b) Both A and R are individually true but R is not explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Knowing the charge is fundamental to preparing a legal defense[span_60](end_span)." },
    { "question": "58. Match Writs with Disputes:\nA. Habeas Corpus - Child custody\nB. Mandamus - Money refund from authority\nC. Quo-Warranto - University teacher appointment\nD. [span_61](start_span)Certiorari - Natural justice violation", "options": ["(a) 1, 3, 2, 4", "(b) 2, 4, 1, 3", "(c) 1, 4, 2, 3", "(d) 2, 3, 1, 4"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Applying writs to specific administrative and civil disputes[span_61](end_span)." },
    { "question": "59. [span_62](start_span)Right to life emanates from:", "options": ["(a) Art 21 and includes right to die", "(b) Art 19 and does not include right to die", "(c) Art 19/20 and includes right to die", "(d) Art 21 and does not include right to die"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "The right to life does not include the right to terminate life (Gian Kaur case)[span_62](end_span)." },
    { "question": "60. [span_63](start_span)Which are exceptions to Art 14 or Art 19?", "options": ["(a) Art 31 A only", "(b) Art 31 C only", "(c) Both 31 A and 31 C", "(d) Neither"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "These articles protect certain laws (like land reforms) from being invalidated by rights articles[span_63](end_span)." },
    { "question": "61. [span_64](start_span)Assertion (A): Art 14 does not require all laws to be universal.\nReason (R): State can classify persons on reasonable grounds.", "options": ["(a) Both A and R are true", "(b) Both A and R are true but R is not explanation", "(c) A is true but R is false", "(d) A is false but R is true"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Reasonable classification is the backbone of Art 14's 'equal protection of laws'[span_64](end_span)." },
    { "question": "62. Special provisions can be made under Art 15 for:\n1. Women and children\n2. STs\n3. Economically backward\n4. [span_65](start_span)Socially backward", "options": ["(a) 1, 2 and 4", "(b) 1 and 3", "(c) 2, 3 and 4", "(d) 1, 2, 3 and 4"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Art 15 originally mentioned women, children, and socially/educationally backward classes or SC/STs[span_65](end_span)." },
    { "question": "63. Consider the following statements:\n1. Quo-warranto safeguards against usurpation of public offices.\n2. [span_66](start_span)HC can issue mandamus to compel a court to exercise jurisdiction.", "options": ["(a) Only 1", "(b) Only 2", "(c) Both 1 and 2", "(d) Neither 1 nor 2"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Both statements correctly identify uses of prerogative writs[span_66](end_span)." },
    { "question": "64. Match the Writs with Implications:\nA. Mandamus - Direction to perform duty\nB. Habeas Corpus - Release of detained person\nC. Certiorari - Case transfer to higher court\nD. [span_67](start_span)Quo-warranto - Show by what authority", "options": ["(a) 1, 2, 3, 4", "(b) 3, 4, 1, 2", "(c) 1, 4, 3, 2", "(d) 3, 2, 1, 4"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Definitions of writ implications[span_67](end_span)." },
    { "question": "65. [span_68](start_span)Freedom of the press in India is:", "options": ["(a) Available under Parliament law", "(b) Specifically provided in Constitution", "(c) Implied in right to expression", "(d) Executive order"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "It is a judicially recognized facet of Article 19(1)(a)[span_68](end_span)." },
    { "question": "66. [span_69](start_span)Right to religion (Art 25) is subject to:", "options": ["(a) Public order, morality and Part III", "(b) Public order, morality and health", "(c) State security restrictions", "(d) Public order, morality, health and Part III"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "The text of Art 25 explicitly lists these three conditions and other Part III provisions[span_69](end_span)." },
    { "question": "67. [span_70](start_span)Which writ examines procedures of inferior Courts?", "options": ["(a) Quo-warranto", "(b) Mandamus", "(c) Prohibition", "(d) Certiorari"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Certiorari reviews the record of a lower court to correct errors of law or jurisdiction[span_70](end_span)." },
    { "question": "68. [span_71](start_span)86th Constitutional Amendment deals with:", "options": ["(a) More state seats", "(b) Women reservation", "(c) Article 21A education", "(d) BC reservation continuation"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "The 86th Amendment made primary education a fundamental right in 2002[span_71](end_span)." },
    { "question": "69. [span_72](start_span)Article automatically suspended on proclamation of emergency:", "options": ["(a) Art 14", "(b) Art 19", "(c) Art 21", "(d) Art 32"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Article 358 causes the automatic suspension of Article 19 rights during a war-based emergency[span_72](end_span)." },
    { "question": "70. [span_73](start_span)Right available to non-citizens:", "options": ["(a) Speech/Assembly", "(b) Move/Reside", "(c) Occupation", "(d) Equality before law"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Article 14 (Equality) applies to all persons; the freedoms under Art 19 are citizen-only[span_73](end_span)." },
    { "question": "71. [span_74](start_span)Writ to free a person illegally detained:", "options": ["(a) Quo-warranto", "(b) Mandamus", "(c) Certiorari", "(d) Habeas Corpus"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Habeas Corpus ('to have the body') is the remedy for unlawful detention[span_74](end_span)." },
    { "question": "72. [span_75](start_span)Untouchability abolished under:", "options": ["(a) Art 14", "(b) Art 15", "(c) Art 16", "(d) Art 17"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "Article 17 abolishes untouchability and forbids its practice in any form[span_75](end_span)." },
    { "question": "73. [span_76](start_span)Amendment adding Art 15(5) for private sector reservation:", "options": ["(a) 81st", "(b) 86th", "(c) 91st", "(d) 93rd"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "The 93rd Amendment (2005) enabled reservations in both state and private educational institutions[span_76](end_span)." },
    { "question": "74. [span_77](start_span)Writ of certiorari is issued to:", "options": ["(a) Stop proceedings", "(b) Transfer record for review", "(c) Show right to office", "(d) Produce detained person"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Unlike Prohibition (which stops), Certiorari brings the record to the higher court to quash orders[span_77](end_span)." },
    { "question": "75. [span_78](start_span)Which statement is NOT correct?", "options": ["(a) Livelihood is facet of life", "(b) Natural justice implicit in Art 21", "(c) Life includes health", "(d) Go abroad is not fundamental"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "The SC in Satwant Singh and Maneka Gandhi held the right to go abroad is part of personal liberty[span_78](end_span)." },
    { "question": "76. [span_79](start_span)Correct statement regarding Mandamus:", "options": ["(a) Against legislature", "(b) performance of public duty", "(c) For discretionary powers", "(d) deciding legality of arrest"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Mandamus is issued to a public official to perform a duty they have failed to do[span_79](end_span)." },
    { "question": "77. [span_80](start_span)Right that CANNOT be taken away during emergency:", "options": ["(a) Speak", "(b) Movement", "(c) Life", "(d) Organize"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Article 21 (Life) is immune from suspension[span_80](end_span)." },
    { "question": "78. [span_81](start_span)Right to property removed by which Amendment?", "options": ["(a) 73rd", "(b) 23rd", "(c) 44th", "(d) 76th"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "The 44th Amendment (1978) moved it from Art 31 to Art 300A[span_81](end_span)." },
    { "question": "79. Match the Writs with Meanings:\nA. Habeas Corpus - Produce the body\nB. Mandamus - Command to perform duty\nC. Certiorari - Certified or made certain\nD. [span_82](start_span)Quo-Warranto - What warrant or authority"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Literal Latin meanings of the writ names[span_82](end_span)." },
    { "question": "80. [span_83](start_span)Community declared minority based on:", "options": ["(a) Religion only", "(b) Either religion or language", "(c) Either language or caste", "(d) Religion or race"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Article 30 specifically mentions religious and linguistic minorities[span_83](end_span)." },
    { "question": "81. [span_84](start_span)Article 30 deals with:", "options": ["(a) Conscience", "(b) Propagate religion", "(c) Establish minority institutions", "(d) Majority cultural rights"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Article 30 is the Charter of Minority Educational Rights[span_84](end_span)." },
    { "question": "82. [span_85](start_span)93rd amendment deals with:", "options": ["(a) Right to education", "(b) Handicapped rights", "(c) Reservation for admission", "(d) Promotion reservations"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "It added Art 15(5) allowing reservation for OBCs/SCs/STs in education[span_85](end_span)." },
    { "question": "83. [span_86](start_span)Writ declaring 'respondent not entitled to office he was holding':", "options": ["(a) Habeas Corpus", "(b) Prohibition", "(c) Quo-Warranto", "(d) Certiorari"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Quo-Warranto ('By what authority') challenges the title to a public office[span_86](end_span)." },
    { "question": "84. [span_87](start_span)President CANNOT suspend rights in which Articles?", "options": ["(a) 20 and 21", "(b) 19 and 20", "(c) 21 and 22", "(d) 19 and 21"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "Article 359 is restricted from suspending enforcement of Articles 20 and 21[span_87](end_span)." },
    { "question": "85. [span_88](start_span)Which is NOT covered under Article 20?", "options": ["(a) Ex post facto laws", "(b) Preventive detention", "(c) Double jeopardy", "(d) Self-incrimination"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Preventive detention is covered under Article 22, not Article 20[span_88](end_span)." }
